d-color: #F5F5F5; border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003eゲストスピーカーの人数\u003c/td\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003e0\u003c/td\u003e\n    \u003c/tr\u003e\n    \u003ctr\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"background-color: #F5F5F5; border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003e履修選抜・課題タイプ=テキスト登録可\u003c/td\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003efalse\u003c/td\u003e\n    \u003c/tr\u003e\n    \u003ctr\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"background-color: #F5F5F5; border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003e履修選抜・選抜課題タイプ=ファイル登録可\u003c/td\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003efalse\u003c/td\u003e\n    \u003c/tr\u003e\n    \u003ctr\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"background-color: #F5F5F5; border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003eGIGAサティフィケート対象\u003c/td\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003etrue\u003c/td\u003e\n    \u003c/tr\u003e\n    \u003ctr\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"background-color: #F5F5F5; border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003e最終更新日\u003c/td\u003e\n      \u003ctd style=\"border-color: #C7CDD1;\"\u003e2020/08/26 15:08:28\u003c/td\u003e\n    \u003c/tr\u003e\n  \u003c/tbody\u003e\n\u003c/table\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\u003ch3 style=\"background-color: #394B58; color: white; padding-left: 8px; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e科目概要\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis is a course on U.S. foreign policy with a specific focus on domestic factors which shapes and influences U.S. foreign policy making process. Despite the popular argument of U.S. retreat and decline, U.S. still remains the world's preeminent power. However, it is difficult to deny that U.S. is increasingly becoming an \"exhausted power.\" The American public has become inward-looking as a result of a decade of excess intervention in the 2000s. The polarization of politics is having a negative effect on U.S. presence on the world stage. Budgetary constraint is limiting the overseas deployment of U.S. forces. The course will try to factor in the domestic constraints in foreign policy making as well as highlight the dynamics of interest group politics that shape foreign policy environment in the U.S.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 style=\"background-color: #394B58; color: white; padding-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e授業シラバス\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003ch4 style=\"background-color: #ccecff; padding-left: 8px; margin-top: 0; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e主題と目標／授業の手法など\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eLecture, textbook, and term paper are all in English. Students are required to acquire basic facts and historical knowledge about U.S. foreign policy by reading such text as, Joyce P. Kaufman, A Concise History of U.S. Foreign Policy 3rd ed. (Lanham: Roman \u0026amp; Littlefield, 2014). This is not a course on U.S. diplomatic history. Rather, it will focus on inner dynamics of contemporary U.S. foreign policy making. \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 style=\"background-color: #ccecff; padding-left: 8px; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e教材・参考文献\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSteven W. Hook, U.S. Foreign Policy: Paradox of World Power, 6th ed. (Washington DC: CQ Press, 2020).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 style=\"background-color: #ccecff; padding-left: 8px; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e提出課題・試験・成績評価の方法など\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAttendance, class work, term paper\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 style=\"background-color: #ccecff; padding-left: 8px; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e履修上の注意\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eLecture, textbook, and exams are all in English.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\u003ch4 style=\"background-color: #ccecff; padding-left: 8px; font-weight: bold;\"\u003e授業計画\u003c/h4\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第1回 Introduction\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eObjective of the course.\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第2回 U.S. in a Turbulent World\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eState of where we are.\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第3回 Expansion of U.S. Power\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eHow powerful is the US?\u003cbr\u003eIs it in decline?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第4回 Dynamics of Decision Making\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eHow do decisions get made?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第5回 Executive Branch\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIs the US President “most powerful man” on the planet?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第6回 Congressional Role\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eCongress has a constitutionally defined foreign policy role.\u003cbr\u003e100 members in the senate and 435 members in the House.\u003cbr\u003e535 voices altogether.\u003cbr\u003eIs it too Chaotic?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第7回 Foreign Policy Bureaucracy\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eWhat are the role of bureaucrats?\u003cbr\u003eWhat do diplomats do?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第8回 Public Opinion\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eDoes public opinion enlighten US foreign policy or is it a distraction?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第9回 Role of Mass Media\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eDo media enlighten or emflame?\u003cbr\u003eThe role of tribal media in politics.\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第10回 Social Movements and Interest Groups\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eYou’ve all heard about Indian lobby, Jewish lobby, Taiwan lobby, and others.\u003cbr\u003eThere are also issue-oriented interest groups.\u003cbr\u003eHow powerful are they?\u003cbr\u003eDo they get to the shape the policy?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第11回 National Security and Defense Policy\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eAmerica today is a “National Security State.”\u003cbr\u003eIts reach encompass the globe.\u003cbr\u003eHow are those missions defined?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第12回 Economic Statecraft \u0026amp; Transnational Policy Issues\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSanctions and other economic state crafts have become an often used tool in foreign policy.\u003cbr\u003eIs it effective?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMany of the issues US faces are transnational issues in nature which it cannot solve alone.\u003cbr\u003eHow is US doing on that front?\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第13回 Discussion\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第14回 Discussion\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003cu\u003e第15回 Discussion\u003c/u\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003e\n  \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n  \n  \u003cp\u003e  \u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003chr\u003e\n\n  \u003cu\u003e15回目に相当するその他の授業計画\u003c/u\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\n  \u003cp\u003eSupplementary class if needed\u003c/p\u003e\n  \u003cp style=\"color: #856a5d;\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n","course_code":"地域と社会（米州）","default_view":"modules","root_account_id":1,"enrollment_term_id":3,"license":null,"grade_passback_setting":null,"end_at":null,"public_syllabus":false,"public_syllabus_to_auth":true,"storage_quota_mb":30000,"is_public_to_auth_users":true,"term":{"id":3,"name":"2020年秋学期","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"created_at":"2020-09-03T21:25:41Z","workflow_state":"active","grading_period_group_id":null},"apply_assignment_group_weights":false,"calendar":{"ics":"https://sol.sfc.keio.ac.jp/feeds/calendars/course_jRHzXqHvLFTUC0WbjStHOVzDJZsJOS2yLOtakZB7.ics"},"time_zone":"Asia/Tokyo","blueprint":false,"enrollments":[],"hide_final_grades":false,"workflow_state":"available","restrict_enrollments_to_course_dates":false,"overridden_course_visibility"